properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snow, and possible ice pellets and freezing rain. Total snowfall: near 15 cm, and possibly more. Location: Iles-de-la-Madeleine. Time span: tonight through Saturday morning. Remarks: Periods of snow will continue tonight and Friday. The snow is expected to become mixed with ice pellets on Friday afternoon and possibly with freezing rain Friday evening, before the precipitation changes back to snow later on Friday night. At this time, forecast guidance indicates that the area of heaviest snowfall will remain just west of the Islands, but this could change if the track of the system bringing the snow shifts further to the east. Strong northeasterly winds on Friday afternoon and evening, followed by strong northwesterly winds early Saturday morning, will cause reduced visibility in snow and blowing snow. Snow is expected to taper off to flurries Saturday morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A fast-moving deepening low pressure system is approaching the South Coast of B.C. Strong winds will affect coastal B.C. from midday Friday until Saturday morning. Western sections of Vancouver Island from Zeballos to Sooke are currently under a wind warning. The low is forecast to approach northern Vancouver Island Friday afternoon and then track across Vancouver Island in the evening. Ahead of the low, strong southeast winds up to 70 km/h can be expected over northern sections of east Vancouver Island and Sunshine Coast Friday afternoon. Strong southwest winds of 50 to 70 km/h will affect southern sections of Victoria near Juan De Fuca Strait, such as Esquimalt, downtown Victoria, the Southern Gulf Islands, Inland Vancouver Island, and over southern sections of Metro Vancouver and western Fraser Valley. Behind the track of the low, strong northwest winds up to 70 km/h are expected to sweep through the Strait of Georgia and may affect western sections of Metro Vancouver near the Strait of Georgia. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heavy snowfall with blowing snow is expected. Total snowfall: 25 to 40 cm (western Newfoundland) and 15 to 30 cm (Great Northern Peninsula). Maximum wind gusts: east to northeasterly 60 to 80 km/h. Locations: western and northern Newfoundland. Time span: this afternoon until noon Saturday. Remarks: Flurries this morning over western Newfoundland will give way to snow, at times heavy, this afternoon. The heavy snow will spread to the Great Northern Peninsula this evening, in conjunction with strengthening winds resulting in blowing snow. The snow may also mix with ice pellets in the Bay of Islands and Gros Morne areas overnight. The snow and wind are forecast to begin easing around noon on Saturday. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
